title: Aust bonds lower after equities carnage
text:
Tue, Aug 25, 2015, 8:53 AM AEST - Australia Markets open in 1 hr 7 mins Aust bonds lower after equities carnage AAP â€“ 10 minutes ago Print 
The Australian bond market is slightly weaker after wild swings on the back of another brutal international equity market session. 
National Australia Bank head of interest rate strategy Skye Masters said big gains occurred around the open of US stocks, which dropped more than six per cent in the first moments of trade. 
Westpac strategist Imre Speizer said US treasuries boosted as the panic on global sharemarkets was interpreted as a deal-breaker for a US Federal Reserve interest rate rise next month. 
"Pricing for a Fed hike in September was pared back to a 20 per cent chance," he said. 
But the local market has since given back much of its gains in volatile trade. 
While Australian bond prices had big swings, they were fairly muted in comparison to other markets, Ms Masters said. 
At 0830 AEST on Tuesday, the September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.450 (implying a yield of 2.550 per cent), down from 97.470 (2.530 per cent) on Monday. 
The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.300 (1.700 per cent), unchanged. 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.702pct, from 1.695pct on Monday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.573pct, from 2.569pct 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* September 2015 bill futures, 97.950, from 97.940 
* December 2015 bill futures, 98.100, unchanged 
(*Closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
